ce:section.ce:para:
In ORR, depending of the catalysts, the oxygen reaction can be governed by two- and four-electron pathways [55,56]. In PEMFCs, the four-electron mechanism is desired, which can either be dissociative or associative. The associative mechanism involves three intermediates (OOH, O, and OH), whereas the dissociative pathway involves two (O and OH) [56]. In the last decade, great efforts have been made for theoretical research of novel catalysts using the intermediates adsorption energy as predictors of catalytic activity for the ORR. Nørskov and collaborators found a tendency volcano type to correlate the catalytic activity and the oxygen adsorption energy of various transition-metal. They demonstrated that pure Pt is not a perfect catalyst. Therefore, better catalysts than Pt can be designed. Later, the research was extended to bimetallic systems [57]. The O adsorption energy was investigated on Pt3M (M = Fe, Co, Ni, and Ti) alloys and correlated with the activity of the Pt3M alloys. It was found that the bimetallic systems presented oxygen adsorption energies more optimal than Pt and consequently a higher catalytic activity than Pt for the ORR. It was also possible to investigate that the best catalysts must have an oxygen adsorption energy of 0.2 eV less than Pt [58]. From these studies, several proposals have been developed using the intermediates adsorption energy as predictors of catalytic activity for ORR [8,9,13,27,59–61]. Thus, in this study, an oxygen atom was used to study the reactivity of the Pdn (n = 8–10) clusters supported on pristine, doped, and defective GQDs toward the ORR. The oxygen was adsorbed in the same site on the Pdn, Pdn/C96H24, Pdn/C95H24:B, and Pdn/C95H24 (n = 8–10) (see Fig. 7
                        ). The oxygen adsorption energies calculated on the Pdn, Pdn/C96H24, Pdn/C95H24:B, and Pdn/C95H24 (n = 8–10) are presented in Fig. 8
                        . All the oxygen adsorption energies calculated in this study are around −4 eV. The reactivity of Pdn (n = 8–10) clusters is not significantly different when they are supported on C96H24, C95H24:B, or C95H24 sheets; however, the Pd8/C96H24, Pd8/C95H24:B, Pd9/C95H24:B, and Pd10/C95H24 composites are promising candidates for the ORR because they offer a more reduction in the oxygen adsorption energy compared to their palladium counterparts. It has been reported that a decrease in oxygen adsorption energy may be directly associated with a greater catalytic activity for ORR in an acidic medium [8,9,13,57].
